# DevOps & Deployment

Coding patterns for environment management, containerization, CI/CD pipelines, and deployment. IF your project has a deployment pipeline, apply these patterns.

> All numeric values in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Environment Management

**MUST** update `.env.example` when adding or changing environment variables (placeholders only - never secrets). Details: `security.md` for secret handling in logs.

**CI capability test:** Apply CI/CD sections below only when the project has a pipeline (e.g. `.github/workflows/`, GitLab CI, etc.). If no CI exists, do not invent pipelines unless the task is to add CI. When CI exists, change only what the task requires; **ask user first** for unrelated workflow edits.

---

### Environment Tiers

```
local       Developer machine - runs everything locally
development Shared dev server - latest code, test data, may break
staging     Pre-production - mirrors production, final testing
production  Live users - zero tolerance for unverified changes
```

**Rules:**
- Every tier has its OWN database (never share databases between environments)
- Every tier has its OWN secrets (different API keys, JWT secrets, etc.)
- Staging mirrors production as closely as possible (same OS, same services, same config)
- Code flows one direction: local -> development -> staging -> production

### Environment Variables

```
Recommended structure:

.env.example          <- Committed. Template with dummy values and comments.
.env                  <- NOT committed. Local overrides.
.env.local            <- NOT committed. Machine-specific overrides.
.env.development      <- NOT committed. Development tier values.
.env.staging          <- NOT committed. Staging tier values.
.env.production       <- NEVER on disk. Managed by secret manager / hosting platform.
```

### .env.example Format

The `.env.example` file should follow this **structure** - the actual variables depend on your stack and services:

```bash
# Application
APP_ENV=development
PORT=3000
APP_URL=http://localhost:3000

# Database (your database's connection string format)
DATABASE_URL=<connection-string-for-your-database>

# Authentication (if applicable)
JWT_SECRET=replace-with-64-char-random-string
SESSION_EXPIRY_HOURS=24

# External Services (only include sections your project actually uses)
# SMTP_HOST=...
# STORAGE_BUCKET=...
# CACHE_URL=...
```

**Rules:**
- **Every** environment variable used in code MUST appear in `.env.example`
- Group variables by service with section comments
- Include brief description for non-obvious variables
- Use a validation function at app startup that checks all required env vars exist and crashes immediately with a clear error if any are missing
- Critical env vars (like `JWT_SECRET`, `DATABASE_URL`) should have no fallback - the app should refuse to start with a clear error. Non-critical vars (like `LOG_LEVEL`, feature flags) can have sensible defaults.

### URL / Config Fallback Chains

When a URL or config value can come from multiple sources (deploy platform, env var, default), use a deterministic fallback chain:

```
Pattern:
  function getBaseUrl():
    -> process.env.PRIMARY_URL          // explicit config (highest priority)
    -> process.env.PLATFORM_URL         // auto-set by hosting platform (Vercel, Railway, etc.)
    -> "http://localhost:3000"           // local dev fallback (lowest priority)
```

- Document the priority sequence in a comment next to the function
- Log which source was used at startup (INFO level) so you can debug config issues
- Never silently fall through to localhost in production - add a WARN log if using the fallback in non-dev environments

