## CI/CD Pipeline

### Pipeline Stages

**Principle:** Every code change passes through an automated pipeline that validates quality before reaching production.

[REFERENCE] Typical pipeline stages:

```
1. INSTALL       -> Install dependencies (cached)
2. LINT          -> Run linter (ESLint, Ruff, etc.)
3. TYPE CHECK    -> Run type checker (tsc, mypy, etc.)
4. UNIT TEST     -> Run unit tests with coverage
5. BUILD         -> Build production artifacts
6. INTEGRATION   -> Run integration tests (if applicable)
7. E2E           -> Run E2E tests (if applicable)
8. SECURITY      -> Dependency audit (npm audit, etc.)
9. DEPLOY        -> Deploy to target environment (if triggered)
```

### CI Triggers

**Principle:** Define which pipeline stages run on which branches. Not every check needs to run on every push.

[REFERENCE] Common trigger configuration:

```
On every push to any branch:
  -> Stages 1-4 (lint, type, unit test)

On PR to main/develop:
  -> Stages 1-8 (full pipeline)

On merge to main:
  -> Stages 1-8 + deploy to staging

On tag (v*.*.*):
  -> Stages 1-8 + deploy to production
```

### Rules

- **CI MUST pass before merge** - emergency bypasses require a follow-up fix PR within the same day (aligned with git-workflow.md)
- **Run the real production build in CI** - for SSR/SSG frameworks (Next.js, Nuxt, SvelteKit, etc.) a passing type check is NOT enough; the production build catches RSC/server-client boundary errors, bad imports, and build-time data failures that only surface at build. Build every deployable app.
- **Cache dependencies** between runs (node_modules, pip cache, etc.)
- **Parallel jobs** where possible (lint and type check run simultaneously)
- **Fail fast** - if lint fails, don't bother running tests
- **Branch protection** on main: require CI pass + PR review
- **Artifacts** - store build output, test reports, coverage reports
- **Timeouts** - set max duration for each stage (prevent hanging CI)
- **Alerts** - notify on CI failure (via configured channel: webhook, team notifier, etc.)

### CI Configuration

Use your CI platform's configuration format (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, CircleCI, Jenkins, etc.). The **structural pattern** is:

```
Job 1 - Quality:
  -> Checkout code
  -> Set up runtime (pinned version, with dependency cache)
  -> Install dependencies
  -> Run linter
  -> Run type checker
  -> Run tests with coverage
  -> Run dependency audit

Job 2 - Build (depends on Quality):
  -> Checkout code
  -> Install dependencies
  -> Build production artifacts
```

**Rules:**
- Pin runtime/tool versions in CI (same as local development)
- Cache dependencies between runs (speeds up CI significantly)
- Use your CI platform's secret management for credentials (never inline)

