## Deployment

### Deployment Strategies

```
Rolling Update (default):
  - Replace instances one at a time
  - Zero downtime
  - Easy rollback (keep previous version running)

Blue-Green:
  - Two identical environments (blue = current, green = new)
  - Switch traffic from blue to green
  - Instant rollback (switch back)
  - Requires 2x resources

Canary:
  - Route small % of traffic to new version
  - Monitor for errors
  - Gradually increase traffic
  - Rollback if errors spike
```

### Deployment Checklist

```
Before every production deploy:
  - [ ] All CI checks pass
  - [ ] Tested in staging environment
  - [ ] Database migrations run successfully (if applicable)
  - [ ] Environment variables set in production
  - [ ] Rollback plan documented
  - [ ] Team notified of deployment window
  - [ ] Observability tools ready

After every production deploy:
  - [ ] Smoke test critical flows (core system paths / critical endpoints)
  - [ ] Check error rates in monitoring
  - [ ] Check response times
  - [ ] Verify database connectivity
  - [ ] Tag the release in git
  - [ ] Update changelog
```

### First Launch / Go-Live Runbook

The **first** production launch needs more than the per-deploy checklist - there is no "previous version" to fall back to and no traffic history. Keep a project-specific go-live runbook (a `docs/go-live.md`) and run it once before the first public release. Template categories:

```
PRE-LAUNCH (days before):
  - [ ] All production env vars set in the secret manager / host (cross-checked against .env.example)
  - [ ] Production database provisioned, migrated, seeded with real reference data; backups enabled
  - [ ] Custom domain + TLS configured; HTTPS forced; www/apex redirect decided
  - [ ] Security headers verified on production (CSP, HSTS, etc. - see security.md)
  - [ ] Third-party services in LIVE mode (payments, email, storage) with production keys + webhooks pointed at prod
  - [ ] Error tracking + uptime monitoring + log aggregation receiving production events
  - [ ] Rate limits, robots/sitemap, and legal pages (privacy, terms) in place
  - [ ] Load/perf sanity check on the hot paths

LAUNCH:
  - [ ] Deploy from a tagged release; smoke test every critical user + admin flow on prod
  - [ ] Place a real end-to-end transaction (if commerce) and confirm money + webhook + receipt
  - [ ] Confirm cache warm/invalidation behaves on prod (no stale public data after an admin edit)

POST-LAUNCH (first 24-72h):
  - [ ] Watch error rate, latency, and resource use closely; have rollback ready
  - [ ] Verify scheduled jobs / cron actually run in prod (check last-run timestamps)
  - [ ] Verify worker processes stay up, reconnect after deploy, and log heartbeats
  - [ ] Confirm backups ran and are restorable
```

Adapt and prune per project; the point is a single, reviewed checklist owned in `docs/` so launch is not improvised.

### Rollback

```
Rules:
  - Deployments should be rollback-able quickly (target: under [DEFAULT] 10 minutes). Irreversible data migrations require a separate, carefully-planned rollback strategy.
  - Keep previous version's artifacts/images for at least [DEFAULT] 5 releases
  - Database migrations must be backward-compatible (new code works with old schema AND new schema)
  - Feature flags for risky features (disable without rollback)
  - Document rollback steps for each deployment method
```

