## Infrastructure as Code

```
Rules:
  - Define ALL infrastructure in code (Terraform, Pulumi, CloudFormation, etc.)
  - Version control infrastructure code alongside application code
  - Review infrastructure changes like code changes (PR + review)
  - NEVER make manual changes to production infrastructure (always through code)
  - Use modules/templates for common patterns (don't repeat server configs)
  - Tag all resources with: environment, project, owner, cost-center
```

---

## Secrets Management

```
Hierarchy (least to most secure):
  1. .env files (development only - NEVER production)
  2. CI/CD secrets (GitHub Secrets, GitLab CI Variables)
  3. Cloud secret managers (AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager, HashiCorp Vault)

Rules:
  - Production secrets ONLY in a managed secret store
  - Rotate secrets on a schedule (at minimum: quarterly)
  - Audit secret access (who accessed what, when)
  - Revoke immediately on team member departure or suspected breach
  - Different secrets per environment (dev JWT secret !== prod JWT secret)
  - Secrets in CI: use built-in secret variables, never echo/print them in logs
```

---

## Monitoring & Alerting Setup

```
Recommended capabilities for production deployments:
  1. Error tracking (dedicated service - e.g., Sentry, Bugsnag, or your platform's equivalent)
  2. Uptime monitoring (regular health check polling)
  3. Performance monitoring (response times, CPU, memory)
  4. Log aggregation (centralized, searchable)
  5. Alerts - define thresholds per project for:
     - Error rate spikes (warning and critical tiers)
     - Response time degradation (separate SLOs for interactive vs heavy endpoints)
     - Service downtime
     - Resource exhaustion (disk, memory, CPU)
```
